member.summary: Represents coordinate system not supported by the Object Model

member.summary: Alignment at Epoch: an inertial system coincident with ECF at the Coord Epoch. Often used to specify launch trajectories.

member.name: F:AGI.STKUtil.AgECoordinateSystem.eCoordinateSystemB1950
member.summary: B1950: X points toward the mean vernal equinox and Z points along the mean rotation axis of the Earth at the beginning of the Besselian year 1950 and corresponds to 31 December 1949 22:09:07.2 or JD 2433282.423.

member.name: F:AGI.STKUtil.AgECoordinateSystem.eCoordinateSystemFixed
member.summary: Fixed: X is fixed at 0 deg longitude, Y is fixed at 90 deg longitude, and Z is directed toward the north pole.

member.name: F:AGI.STKUtil.AgECoordinateSystem.eCoordinateSystemJ2000
member.summary: J2000: X points toward the mean vernal equinox and Z points along the mean rotation axis of the Earth on 1 Jan 2000 at 12:00:00.00 TDB, which corresponds to JD 2451545.0 TDB.

member.name: F:AGI.STKUtil.AgECoordinateSystem.eCoordinateSystemMeanOfDate
member.summary: Mean of Date: X points toward the mean vernal equinox and Z points along the mean rotation axis of the Earth at the Orbit Epoch.

member.name: F:AGI.STKUtil.AgECoordinateSystem.eCoordinateSystemMeanOfEpoch
member.summary: Mean of Epoch: X points toward the mean vernal equinox and Z points along the mean rotation axis of the Earth at the Coord Epoch.

member.name: F:AGI.STKUtil.AgECoordinateSystem.eCoordinateSystemTEMEOfDate
member.summary: TEME of Date: X points toward the mean vernal equinox and Z points along the true rotation axis of the Earth at the Orbit Epoch.

member.name: F:AGI.STKUtil.AgECoordinateSystem.eCoordinateSystemTEMEOfEpoch
member.summary: TEME of Epoch: X points toward the mean vernal equinox and Z points along the true rotation axis of the Earth at the Coord Epoch.

member.name: F:AGI.STKUtil.AgECoordinateSystem.eCoordinateSystemTrueOfDate
member.summary: True of Date: X points toward the true vernal equinox and Z points along the true rotation axis of the Earth at the Orbit Epoch.

member.name: F:AGI.STKUtil.AgECoordinateSystem.eCoordinateSystemTrueOfEpoch
member.summary: True of Epoch: X points toward the true vernal equinox and Z points along the true rotation axis of the Earth at the Coord Epoch.

member.name: F:AGI.STKUtil.AgECoordinateSystem.eCoordinateSystemTrueOfRefDate
member.summary: True of Ref Date: A special case of True of Epoch. Instead of the Coord Epoch, this system uses a Reference Date defined in the Integration Control page of the scenario's PODS properties.

summary.para: This method is similar to QueryPlanetocentric but can be used by earlybound(c#, vb.net...) and latebound(scripting languages) clients. The array returns the values in the order Latitude(index 0), Longitude(index 1) and Altitude(index 2).

This method is similar to QueryPlanetodetic but can be used by earlybound(c#, vb.net...) and latebound(scripting languages) clients. The array returns the values in the order Latitude(index 0), Longitude(index 1) and Altitude(index 2).

This method is similar to QuerySpherical but can be used by earlybound(c#, vb.net...) and latebound(scripting languages) clients. The array returns the values in the order Latitude(index 0), Longitude(index 1) and Radius(index 2).

This method is similar to QueryCylindrical but can be used by earlybound(c#, vb.net...) and latebound(scripting languages) clients. The array returns the values in the order Radius(index 0), Lon(index 1) and Z(index 2).

This method is similar to QueryCartesian but can be used by earlybound(c#, vb.net...) and latebound(scripting languages) clients. The array returns the values in the order X(index 0), Y(index 1) and Z(index 2).

returns.para: A one dimensional array containing three values X, Y and Z.

member.summary: Geodetic: position specified in terms of latitude (angle between the normal to the reference ellipsoid and the equatorial plane), longitude and altitude.

member.name: F:AGI.STKUtil.AgEPositionType.eSpherical
member.summary: Spherical: position specified in terms of latitude (spherical latitude of the sub-point on the surface of the Earth), longitude and radius (distance of the object from the center of the Earth).

member.name: F:AGI.STKUtil.AgEPositionType.ePlanetocentric
member.summary: Planetocentric: position specified in terms of latitude (spherical latitude of the sub-point on the surface of the Earth), longitude and altitude.

member.name: F:AGI.STKUtil.AgEPositionType.ePlanetodetic
member.summary: Planetodetic: position specified in terms of latitude (angle between the normal to the reference ellipsoid and the equatorial plane), longitude and altitude.

This method is similar to QueryPlanetodetic but can be used by earlybound(c#, vb.net...) and latebound(scripting languages) clients. The array returns the values in the order Latitude(index 0), Longitude(index 1) and Altitude(index 2).

This method is similar to QuerySpherical but can be used by earlybound(c#, vb.net...) and latebound(scripting languages) clients. The array returns the values in the order Latitude(index 0), Longitude(index 1) and Radius(index 2).

This method is similar to QueryCylindrical but can be used by earlybound(c#, vb.net...) and latebound(scripting languages) clients. The array returns the values in the order Radius(index 0), Lon(index 1) and Z(index 2).

This method is similar to QueryCartesian but can be used by earlybound(c#, vb.net...) and latebound(scripting languages) clients. The array returns the values in the order X(index 0), Y(index 1) and Z(index 2).

returns.para: A one dimensional array containing three values X, Y and Z.

summary.para: This method is similar to QueryPlanetocentric but can be used by earlybound(c#, vb.net...) and latebound(scripting languages) clients. The array returns the values in the order Latitude(index 0), Longitude(index 1) and Altitude(index 2).

This method is similar to QueryPlanetodetic but can be used by earlybound(c#, vb.net...) and latebound(scripting languages) clients. The array returns the values in the order Latitude(index 0), Longitude(index 1) and Altitude(index 2).

This method is similar to QuerySpherical but can be used by earlybound(c#, vb.net...) and latebound(scripting languages) clients. The array returns the values in the order Latitude(index 0), Longitude(index 1) and Radius(index 2).

This method is similar to QueryCylindrical but can be used by earlybound(c#, vb.net...) and latebound(scripting languages) clients. The array returns the values in the order Radius(index 0), Lon(index 1) and Z(index 2).

This method is similar to QueryCartesian but can be used by earlybound(c#, vb.net...) and latebound(scripting languages) clients. The array returns the values in the order X(index 0), Y(index 1) and Z(index 2).

returns.para: A one dimensional array containing three values X, Y and Z.
